            posterior tips of the LH, the thalamus immediately dorsal
            to the LH, the amygdala just lateral to the LH, or the
            paraventricular and perifornical areas medial to the
            LH. The results show that across doses and agonists the
            eating-stimulatory effects were largest with injections
            into the LH. In the LH, glutamate between 300 and 900 nmol
            elicited a dose-dependent eating response of up to 5 g
            within 1 h (P < 0.01). Each of the other agonists at doses
            of 3.3 nmol or less elicited eating responses of at least
            10 g with injections into this site. Injections into the
            other brain sites produced either no eating, or
            occasionally smaller and less consistent eating
            responses.(ABSTRACT TRUNCATED AT 250 WORDS)}",

journal = "Brain Res",
year = "1993",
volume = "630",
number = "1-2",
pages = "41-49",
